message.content:
We can “derive” the net profit by (roughly) “adding up” all the income‐generating items (the “Sale” transactions’ “profit” values plus the “Interest Receivables” amounts) and then “subtracting” all the outgo‐ings (all the “Expense” and “Depreciation” transaction amounts). (In our books the inventory “Purchases” and the “Transfer” and “Initial” entries are balance transfers and do not affect the “profit” calculation.) 

Step‐by step (numbers are rounded as we work “by hand”):

1. • Gather all “Sale” rows. Their “profit” fields are (in currency units):

  1498.27, 11935.53, 14374.65, 16770.88, 7806.75, 16898.14, 159298.95, 5930.91, 70550.84, 17132.14, 34717.66, 144182.5, 3652.08, 4428.82, 5216.28, 120407.25, 14504.76, 9166.45, 31037.8, 15890.52, 52207.52, 5553.24, 9687.4, 17441.68, 14724.52, 52114.2, 13470.62, 111855.06, 65712.0, 7800.68, 22693.5, 28615.27, 34146.46, 97428.88, 9663.3, 35563.82, 75061.65, 10440.8, 11846.6, 56035.5, 10289.32, 7306.1.

 Summing these (step‐by‐step) we obtain an approximate total sale “profit” of about 1,454,059.30.

2. • Gather the “Interest Receivables” rows. Their amounts (which are “income” even though they are “receivable”) are roughly:

  420.08, 375.58, 346.68, 291.08, 235.22, then a series of seven records of about 199.62 each, then two records of about 190.72, five records of about 164.02, and finally eleven records of about 135.54.
 When summed the total “Interest Receivables” come to about 5,758.38.

3. • Gather all the “Expense” and “Depreciation” rows (all rows whose type begins with “Expense” or is “Depreciation”). (All the cost‐reducing “expense” items include Financial, Sales, Administrative and the Depreciation value.)
 When we add up all these amounts we find that the total expenses come to about 2,550,849.46.

4. • Then the net profit (on which the cash flow statement “bottom” is based) can be computed as

  Net Profit = (Total profit from Sales + Total Interest income) – (Total Expenses)
    ≈ (1,454,059.30 + 5,758.38) – 2,550,849.46 
    ≈ 1,459,817.68 – 2,550,849.46 
    ≈ –1,091,031.78

Thus, the net “profit” that eventually shows up in the cash‐flow statement is negative (a loss) of about –1,091,031.78.

We therefore return the result rounded (for example, to two decimals) as follows.

Below is the answer in the requested JSON format:

--------------------------------------------------

```json
{"solution": {"Net Profit": "-1091031.78"}}
```
